var definitions = ['<h2>Lukas und Lena sind Freunde.</h2><div><strong>Lukas</strong> This is a German given name used here as the subject of the sentence. It refers to a male individual.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is the German word for "and". It is a conjunction used to connect words or groups of words.</div><div><strong>Lena</strong> Similar to Lukas, this is a German given name and part of the subject in this sentence. Lena refers to a female individual.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It indicates the state of being or the relationship between the subjects and the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Freunde</strong> This is the German word for "friends" (masculine plural form). Here, it indicates the relationship between Lukas and Lena. If they were both female, it would be "Freundinnen".</div>','<h2>Es ist erschwinglich und von guter Qualität.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German neuter pronoun for "it". It’s used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the complementary properties described in the sentence.</div><div><strong>erschwinglich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "affordable". It describes something that can be purchased without causing financial strain.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses that are equally important in the sentence.</div><div><strong>von guter Qualität</strong> This phrase combines the preposition "von", meaning "of", with the phrase "guter Qualität", meaning "good quality". Together, it expresses that the subject has a level of quality that is good or favorable.</div>','<h2>Es gibt Ketchup und Senf auf seinem Hotdog.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. In this sentence, "es" refers to a general existence, similar to "there is" in English.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give" in German. Here, it is used in an impersonal construction that translates to "there is" (or "there are") in English.</div><div><strong>Ketchup</strong> This is a German noun borrowed from English, referring to the tomato-based condiment. In German, nouns are always capitalized.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses.</div><div><strong>Senf</strong> This is a German noun meaning "mustard". Like all German nouns, it is capitalized, and it refers to another popular condiment.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German which can translate to "on" or "upon" in English. It is used here to describe the location of the ketchup and mustard, indicating they are on top of something else.</div><div><strong>seinem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case, masculine singular form, translating to "his" in English. It denotes ownership of the Hotdog by a male referent.</div><div><strong>Hotdog</strong> This is a noun adopted from English into German, referring to the popular food consisting of a sausage placed in a sliced bun. It remains capitalized in German as all nouns do.</div>','<h2>Es gibt Äpfel und Orangen im Korb.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is a pronoun in German, equivalent to the English word "it". "Es" is often used as an impersonal or neutral pronoun and is the subject of this sentence. In the context of this sentence, "es" implies the existence of something.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This word is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give". However, in this context "es gibt" translates to "there are" in English, indicating the presence of something.</div><div><strong>Äpfel</strong> This is the plural form of "Apfel", which means "apple" in English. In this sentence, it’s the direct object that is being referred to by the verb "gibt".</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word is a conjunction in German that means "and". It’s used to connect words and phrases with a similar grammatical status, in this case, "Äpfel" and "Orangen".</div><div><strong>Orangen</strong> This is the plural form of "Orange", which means "orange" in English. Like "Äpfel", it’s also a direct object in the sentence.</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" (similar to the English word "in") and the definite article "dem", which is the dative form of "der" and translates to "the" in English. "im Korb" means "in the basket".</div><div><strong>Korb</strong> This is a German noun meaning "basket". It is the indirect object of the sentence, and it indicates the location of the apples and oranges, which are inside it.</div>','<h2>Ich habe eine Katze und einen Hund.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or ownership in this context.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the indefinite article for feminine singular nouns in the nominative case in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes "Katze" which is a feminine noun.</div><div><strong>Katze</strong> This is the German word for "cat". It is a feminine singular noun in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect nouns in German.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the indefinite article for masculine singular nouns in the accusative case in German. It is used before "Hund", which is a masculine noun, due to the accusative case caused by the verb "haben".</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is the German word for "dog". It is a masculine singular noun. In this sentence, it is in the accusative case.</div>','<h2>Willst du ins Kino oder ins Restaurant gehen?</h2><div><strong>Willst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want" in English. It expresses a desire or intention.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ins</strong> This is a contraction of "in das", a combination of the preposition "in" (meaning "to" or "into") and the neuter article "das" (meaning "the"). "Ins" is used here to indicate movement towards a place.</div><div><strong>Kino</strong> This is a German noun meaning "cinema" or "movie theater". The sentence proposes "Kino" as one of the destinations.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German coordinating conjunction for "or", which presents an alternative.</div><div><strong>ins Restaurant</strong> Similar to the earlier "ins", this combines "in das" with the noun "Restaurant", which is a German noun meaning "restaurant". Here, it’s the second option being offered as a destination.</div><div><strong>gehen?</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "gehen", which means "to go". It indicates the action being considered. The question mark at the end indicates that this is a question.</div>','<h2>Was wirst du essen, den Apfel oder den Kuchen?</h2><div><strong>Was</strong> This is the German interrogative pronoun meaning "what". It is used to start a question.</div><div><strong>wirst</strong> This is the second-person singular future tense conjugation of the verb "werden" which in this case is used to form the future tense, equivalent to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>essen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to eat" in German.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the masculine accusative definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here because "Apfel" and "Kuchen" are both masculine nouns and the direct objects of the verb "essen".</div><div><strong>Apfel</strong> This is the German word for "apple". It is a masculine noun and one of the options being offered to "eat".</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German word for "or". It is a conjunction used to offer a choice between two items.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the masculine accusative definite article repeated before the second option in the list.</div><div><strong>Kuchen</strong> This is the German word for "cake". It is a masculine noun and the alternative choice to the apple.</div>','<h2>Wollen Sie die schwarze Uhr oder die weiße?</h2><div><strong>Wollen</strong> This is the verb "wollen" which means "to want" in English. It indicates a desire or intention.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for addressing someone respectfully. It can refer to one person or several people.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This article means "the" in English. It’s a definite article used here in the accusative case because it’s in the context of a direct object in the sentence.</div><div><strong>schwarze</strong> This is an adjective meaning "black" in English. It’s used here to describe the noun "Uhr" (clock or watch), and it agrees with the noun in gender, number, and case.</div><div><strong>Uhr</strong> This is the noun "Uhr", which means "clock" or "watch" in English. In this sentence, it’s singular and in the accusative case because it’s the direct object.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "or" in English. It’s used to offer a choice between two options.</div><div><strong>die</strong> Again, this article means "the" in English, here repeated before the alternative option presented in the question.</div><div><strong>weiße?</strong> This is an adjective meaning "white" in English. Just like "schwarze", it’s used here to describe the noun "Uhr" (clock or watch) and agrees with the noun in gender, number, and case. The question mark indicates that this is a question, asking which of the two watches the person prefers.</div>','<h2>Ich werde einen neuen Mantel oder einen Hut kaufen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the German first-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular form of the future tense auxiliary verb "werden", which is used here to indicate the future tense, equivalent to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular article "ein" in German, used before the word "Mantel" and "Hut" in this sentence. It is the indefinite article equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>neuen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular form of the adjective "neu", which means "new" in English. It agrees in case, gender, and number with the noun it modifies, which in this sentence is "Mantel".</div><div><strong>Mantel</strong> This is the German word for "coat". It is a masculine singular noun here in the accusative case as it is the direct object of the verb "kaufen".</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German word for "or", used as a conjunction to give an alternative.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is repeated for the second item in the list, again functioning as the accusative masculine singular article "ein", before the word "Hut".</div><div><strong>Hut</strong> This is the German word for "hat". It is also a masculine singular noun here in the accusative case as it is the alternative direct object of the verb "kaufen".</div><div><strong>kaufen</strong> This is a German verb meaning "to buy". It’s presented here in its infinitive form as part of the future tense construction with "werde".</div>','<h2>Welche finden Sie besser? Die graue oder die weiße?</h2><div><strong>Welche</strong> This is a German interrogative pronoun that means "which" or "what" in English. It is used for asking a question when choosing between multiple options.</div><div><strong>finden</strong> This is the second-person formal plural or formal singular of the German verb "finden", which means "to find" in English. In this context, it means to have an opinion or preference.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the sentence and denotes a formal address.</div><div><strong>besser?</strong> This is the comparative form of the German adjective "gut", which means "good". In English, "besser" translates to "better". It’s used to compare two or more things.</div><div><strong>Die graue</strong> This is a combination of the German definite article "die" (feminine nominative or accusative singular form meaning "the") and the adjective "graue" meaning "grey". It refers to a feminine noun (implicitly understood from the context) in the grey color.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German word for "or" and is used as a conjunction to offer a choice between options.</div><div><strong>die weiße?</strong> Similar to "die graue", this phrase consists of the German definite article "die" and the adjective "weiße" which means "white". This phrase is referring to another option, which is something in white color (assuming also feminine noun), and is part of the choice being presented in the question.</div>','<h2>Ich möchte gerne reisen, aber ich habe kein Geld.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the German first-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of both clauses in the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the first-person singular form of the modal verb "möchten", which means "would like to". It’s used here to express a desire or preference.</div><div><strong>gerne</strong> This German adverb means "gladly" or "with pleasure". It’s used with "möchte" to emphasize the desire to do something.</div><div><strong>reisen</strong> This is the German infinitive verb that means "to travel". It’s the main action that the subject wishes to do.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "but", used to connect contrasting statements or clauses.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is repeated as it is the subject of the second clause as well.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this case, it indicates possession.</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a negation word in German, comparable to "no" or "not any" in English. It’s used here to indicate the absence of something, in this case, money.</div><div><strong>Geld</strong> This is the German noun for "money". In the sentence, it’s the direct object that the speaker does not have.</div>','<h2>Ich habe Jannik angerufen, aber er war nicht zu Hause.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense auxiliary verb of "haben" that is used to form the perfect tense, equivalent to "have" in English. It’s used here to form the past tense construction together with the main verb "angerufen".</div><div><strong>Jannik</strong> This is a proper noun, a male first name. In this context, it’s the direct object of the sentence, the person whom the subject called.</div><div><strong>angerufen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "anrufen", which means "to call" in English. Together with "habe", it forms the present perfect tense indicating a completed action in the past.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word is a conjunction meaning "but" in English. It is used to connect contrasting clauses or phrases within a sentence.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the second clause.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It indicates a state or condition in the past.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It negates the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>zu Hause</strong> This phrase means "at home" in English. It describes the location or state of the subject mentioned in the second clause.</div>','<h2>Ich bin zum Restaurant gegangen, aber es war geschlossen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the German first-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". In this context, it is part of the past tense structure "bin gegangen" which is used for the perfect tense in German, conveying the equivalent of "have gone" or "went" in English.</div><div><strong>zum</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "zu", meaning "to", and the definite article "dem", meaning "the". It could be translated as "to the" in English. "Zum Restaurant" means "to the restaurant".</div><div><strong>Restaurant</strong> This is a German noun borrowed from French, and it means "restaurant" in English. In this sentence, it is the destination of the subject.</div><div><strong>gegangen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". Used with "bin", it forms the perfect tense, referring to a completed action in the past, similar to "went".</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is the German word for "but". It’s a conjunction used to introduce a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the German third-person neuter pronoun, equivalent to "it" in English. Here it refers to the "Restaurant".</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". "War" translates to "was" in English and refers to the state of the restaurant being closed at the time the subject went there.</div><div><strong>geschlossen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "schließen", which means "to close". In this sentence, it is used as an adjective to describe the state of the restaurant, which was closed. The past participle is used here without an auxiliary verb, not as part of a verb tense but as an adjective.</div>','<h2>Dieser Kaufmann verkauft kein Gemüse, sondern Obst und Fleisch.</h2><div><strong>Dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this" in English. It is used here in the nominative case and is masculine singular, to refer to "Kaufmann" (merchant).</div><div><strong>Kaufmann</strong> This is a noun meaning "merchant" or "trader" in English. It is masculine singular and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verkauft</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "verkaufen", which means "to sell" in English.</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a negative indefinite article meaning "no" or "not any" in English. It negates the noun that follows it and is used here with "Gemüse" (vegetables).</div><div><strong>Gemüse</strong> This is a noun meaning "vegetables" in English. It is neuter singular here and is the direct object of the verb "verkauft".</div><div><strong>sondern</strong> This is a coordinating conjunction in German meaning "but rather" or simply "but" in English. It is used to introduce a contrast or an alternative.</div><div><strong>Obst</strong> This is a noun meaning "fruit" in English. It is neuter singular and is part of the object, representing an alternative to what the merchant does not sell.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "and" in English. It is used here to connect "Obst" (fruit) with "Fleisch" (meat).</div><div><strong>Fleisch</strong> This is a noun meaning "meat" in English. It is neuter singular and is the final element of the list of goods that the merchant sells.</div>','<h2>Ich komme nicht aus Deutschland, sondern aus Österreich.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>komme</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come". It indicates the subject’s action or movement, often in the context of origin or point of departure in sentences like this.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates the verb that follows and is used to make a negative statement.</div><div><strong>aus</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "from" when indicating the origin or place of where someone is coming from.</div><div><strong>Deutschland</strong> This is a noun and the German name for "Germany". It’s the country that the speaker is negating as their point of origin.</div><div><strong>sondern</strong> This is a coordinating conjunction in German that is used to express a contrast or an alternative. It is comparable to the English conjunction "but rather" or "but instead".</div><div><strong>Österreich</strong> This is a noun and the German name for "Austria". It’s the actual country the speaker originates from, used in contrast to "Deutschland" in this sentence.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Ja, ich spiele Tennis und Fussball.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It confirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spiele</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". It indicates the action that the subject is doing.</div><div><strong>Tennis</strong> This is a noun meaning "tennis" in English. It’s a sport being played by the subject.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses.</div><div><strong>Fussball</strong> This is a noun meaning "football" in English, known as "soccer" in the United States. Like "Tennis", it’s another sport the subject is playing.</div>','<h2>Ich heiße Renate Hoffmann, und Sie?</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>heiße</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "heißen", which means "to be called" or "to be named". It’s used here to tell someone your name.</div><div><strong>Renate Hoffmann</strong> This is a proper noun, being the name of the person speaking. In German, both first and last names are capitalized.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>Sie?</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here at the end of the sentence to ask the person being addressed what their name is or how they are called. In a formal setting, "Sie" is always capitalized.</div>','<h2>Ja, ich habe einen Jungen und ein Mädchen.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It confirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or having something.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the masculine accusative form of the indefinite article "ein", which means "a" or "an" in English. It’s used here because "Jungen" (boy) is masculine and is the direct object of the sentence, thus requiring the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Jungen</strong> This is the German word for "boy". It is a noun in the accusative case, serving as the direct object in this sentence.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the neuter nominative/accusative form of the indefinite article "ein", used here because "Mädchen" (girl) is neutral gender in German and it is also the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Mädchen</strong> This is the German word for "girl". Similar to "Jungen", it’s a noun in the accusative case and is the direct object of this sentence.</div>','<h2>Wir lieben es, zu tanzen und zu singen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>lieben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "lieben", which means "to love". It expresses an action or a state of being that the subject is engaging in.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. In this sentence, it serves as a pronoun referring to an activity or idea, in this case the activities of dancing and singing.</div><div>The phrase <strong>zu tanzen und zu singen</strong> comprises two infinitive verb forms with their respective infinitive constructions "zu tanzen" (to dance) and "zu singen" (to sing). They are connected by the conjunction "und" (and). This structure is used to express the activities that are loved, functioning similarly to an English infinitive phrase.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is a German preposition used here as part of the infinitive construction of the verbs, roughly equivalent to the English "to" used with infinitives.</div><div><strong>tanzen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "tanzen", which means "to dance" in English.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>singen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "singen", which translates to "to sing" in English.</div>','<h2>Es dauert zwischen drei und fünf Tagen.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dauert</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "dauern", which means "to last" or "to take (time)". It indicates the duration of an action.</div><div><strong>zwischen</strong> This is a preposition in German, which means "between". It’s used here to express a range.</div><div><strong>drei</strong> This is the cardinal number "three" in German. It denotes the minimum amount of time in the range.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is a conjunction in German, equivalent to "and" in English. It connects elements of similar functions, in this case, numbers in a range.</div><div><strong>fünf</strong> This is the cardinal number "five" in German. It indicates the maximum amount of time in the range.</div><div><strong>Tagen</strong> This is the dative plural form of "Tag", which means "day" in German. The dative case is used after certain prepositions, like "zwischen", to indicate indirect objects or to express a measure of time.</div>','<h2>Ich habe ein Buch gelesen und viel geschlafen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" in English. It precedes the noun "Buch".</div><div><strong>Buch</strong> This is a German noun meaning "book". It is the direct object of the verb "gelesen" in the sentence.</div><div><strong>gelesen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "lesen", which means "to read". In this sentence, it’s used in the present perfect tense along with the auxiliary verb "habe" to indicate a past action.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>viel</strong> This is an adjective meaning "a lot" or "much" in English. It modifies the verb "geschlafen", enhancing the meaning to indicate a large amount or duration.</div><div><strong>geschlafen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "schlafen", which means "to sleep". Similar to "gelesen", it is used here with the auxiliary verb "habe" to form the present perfect tense and to express that the subject slept a lot.</div>','<h2>Ich habe Atembeschwerden und ich huste.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of both clauses in the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here in conjunction with "Atembeschwerden" to indicate possession or experience of a condition.</div><div><strong>Atembeschwerden</strong> This is a German noun which translates to "breathing difficulties" or "respiratory problems". It’s a composite noun formed from "Atem" (breath) and "Beschwerden" (complaints, troubles).</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses within a sentence.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is repeated as it is still the subject of the following clause, referring back to "I" in English.</div><div><strong>huste</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "husten", which means "to cough". It describes the action being performed by the subject.</div>','<h2>Ich habe mich verirrt und habe keinen Plan...</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here twice to express possession and to indicate the auxiliary verb for the past participle.</div><div><strong>mich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, corresponding to "myself" in English. It indicates that the action of the verb is directed back at the subject.</div><div><strong>verirrt</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "verirren", meaning "to get lost" or "to stray". It is used here with the verb "haben" to form the perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect two clauses or phrases.</div><div><strong>habe</strong>  Again, this is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", used here for the second verb construction in the sentence.</div><div><strong>keinen</strong> This is the negation of "einen", which means "a" or "an" in English, in the accusative case. "Keinen" is a combination of "kein" (none, no) with the masculine accusative ending "en", indicating negation in this context.</div><div><strong>Plan</strong> This is a German noun meaning "plan" or "map". In this case, it probably means that the speaker does not have a plan or a map to find their way.</div>','<h2>Ich möchte wieder und wieder reisen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the first-person singular conjugation of the modal verb "möchten", which means "to want to" or "would like to". It expresses a desire or preference.</div><div><strong>wieder</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "again". In this sentence, it is used twice for emphasis, indicating the desire to travel multiple times.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words or groups of words.</div><div><strong>wieder</strong> Repeated for emphasis, it means "again", underscoring the repeated desire to travel.</div><div><strong>reisen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "reisen", which means "to travel". As it follows the modal verb "möchte", it remains in the infinitive form.</div>','<h2>Sie gibt dir die Gabel und den Löffel.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun in the third-person singular feminine or formal "you" in the second-person singular, depending on context. In this sentence, it means "she" as in "She gives you the fork and the spoon".</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give". It indicates the action being performed by the subject "she".</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the personal pronoun in the dative case, meaning "to you". It indicates the indirect object of the verb "gibt", showing who is receiving the fork and spoon.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the feminine singular article in the accusative case, which accompanies "Gabel" (fork) in this sentence. It translates to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Gabel</strong> This is a German noun meaning "fork". It’s the direct object in the sentence, combined with the article "die" to form "the fork".</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word is a conjunction translating to "and" in English. It connects the two nouns "Gabel" (fork) and "Löffel" (spoon).</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the masculine singular article in the accusative case which accompanies "Löffel" (spoon) in this sentence. It also translates to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Löffel</strong> This is a German noun meaning "spoon". It’s another direct object in the sentence, forming the phrase "and the spoon" in combination with the article "den" and the conjunction "und".</div>','<h2>Ja. Mein Chef und meine Kollegen sind super.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It confirms or affirms a statement.</div><div><strong>Mein</strong> This is the first-person singular possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates possession or a relation to the subject.</div><div><strong>Chef</strong> This is a German noun meaning "boss" or "chief". It denotes the person the speaker is directly reporting to or the person in charge.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words or clauses that appear in a list or sequence.</div><div><strong>meine</strong> Similar to "mein", this is the feminine or plural form of the first-person singular possessive pronoun in German, meaning "my". It indicates possession or a relation to the subject, and changes form to agree with the gender or plurality of the noun it modifies, which in this sentence is "Kollegen".</div><div><strong>Kollegen</strong> This is the German word for "colleagues". It is in the plural form, indicating several coworkers or members of the same team.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject with a state of being or a characteristic.</div><div><strong>super</strong> This term is adopted from English and used in German to convey that something is excellent or great. It is an adjective or modifier that describes the boss and colleagues in a positive light. In this case, it does not change form because it is an invariable adjective.</div>','<h2>Meine Katze ist schwarz und eure ist weiß.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German that means "my". It indicates ownership or a relationship to the speaker, and agrees with the feminine noun "Katze" (cat) which is why it is "meine" and not "mein" (which would be used with masculine or neuter nouns).</div><div><strong>Katze</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that means "cat". In this sentence, it’s the subject that the speaker is talking about.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Katze" with the adjective "schwarz" (black).</div><div><strong>schwarz</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "black". It describes the color of the speaker’s cat.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "and". It is used here to connect the first part of the sentence about the speaker’s cat to the second part about the listener’s cat.</div><div><strong>eure</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German that means "your" in the plural form. It implies ownership or a relationship to the listener, and it agrees in number and case with the noun "Katze" implied in the second part of the sentence.</div><div><i>The word "Katze" is implied in this part of the sentence but not directly stated. It is understood that the subject relates back to the cat mentioned in the first part.</i></div><div><strong>ist</strong> This verb is repeated from earlier in the sentence, also in the third-person singular present tense. It connects the implied subject ("eure Katze") with the adjective "weiß" (white).</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "white". It describes the color of the listener’s cat, contrasting with the speaker’s black cat.</div>','<h2>Gut. Und kennen Sie ein gutes Restaurant?</h2><div><strong>Gut</strong> This is the German word for "good". It can be used to express approval or to confirm that something is satisfactory.</div><div><strong>Und</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses within a sentence.</div><div><strong>kennen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "kennen", which means "to know" in the sense of being acquainted with someone or something.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used in formal situations or to address someone in a polite manner.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the German indefinite article for the nominative masculine or neuter singular, translating as "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>gutes</strong> This is the nominative neuter singular form of the adjective "gut", which means "good" in English. Here, it modifies "Restaurant" and it is declined to agree with the neuter gender of the noun.</div><div><strong>Restaurant</strong> This is a German noun adopted from French, meaning "restaurant". It is neutral in gender and nominative in case in this sentence.</div>','<h2>Ist es ein neues oder ein gebrauchtes Auto?</h2><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It’s the verb of the sentence, forming the question.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter, third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, referring to a neuter noun such as "das Auto" (the car).</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the indefinite article in German for masculine or neuter nouns in the nominative case, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It’s used here twice, once before "neues" and once before "gebrauchtes", both times modifying "Auto".</div><div><strong>neues</strong> This is an adjective meaning "new" in English. In German, adjectives change their endings depending on the case, gender, and definiteness of the noun they modify. Here, "neues" is in the nominative case and is modifying the neuter noun "Auto", with an indefinite article.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "or" in English. It connects the two options being presented in the question.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> As previously mentioned, this is the indefinite article again used in the same context as before but with the second adjective.</div><div><strong>gebrauchtes</strong> This is an adjective meaning "used" or "second-hand" in English. It takes the same case, gender, and definiteness ending as "neues" because it is also modifying the neuter noun "Auto" with an indefinite article.</div><div><strong>Auto?</strong> This is the German word for "car", a neuter noun in the nominative case. It is the object being inquired about, at the end of the question.</div>','<h2>Möchten Sie normal oder Express?</h2><div><strong>Möchten</strong> This is the verb "möchten" in its plural or formal polite form, which is a modal verb used to express a polite desire or preference, similar to "would like" in English.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for addressing someone respectfully or in a formal context. It can refer to a single person or multiple people.</div><div><strong>normal</strong> This word translates directly to "normal" in English. It refers to the standard or regular option.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German word for "or". It’s a conjunction used to offer a choice between two or more items.</div><div><strong>Express?</strong> This is borrowed from English and means "express". In this context, it refers to an expedited or fast service option. The question mark indicates that this is a question, offering the listener a choice between the normal or express option.</div>','<h2>Ist das deine Meinung oder ein Fakt?</h2><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. In this sentence, it sets up a question regarding the nature of a statement.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a neuter demonstrative pronoun in German, equivalent to "that" or "this" in English. It points to the subject being discussed.</div><div><strong>deine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the second-person singular, equivalent to "your" in English. It denotes ownership or relation to the person spoken to.</div><div><strong>Meinung</strong> This is a feminine noun meaning "opinion" in English. It refers to a personal belief or view.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is a coordinating conjunction equivalent to "or" in English. It provides an alternative option or choice.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in the masculine or neuter form, which translates to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun "Fakt".</div><div><strong>Fakt</strong> This is a masculine noun equivalent to "fact" in English. It implies something that is objectively true, rather than subjective opinion.</div><div><strong>?</strong> The question mark denotes that the sentence is a question, prompting the respondent to clarify whether the statement in question is an opinion or a fact.</div>','<h2>Auf Ihr Girokonto oder Ihr Sparkonto?</h2><div><strong>Auf</strong> This is a German preposition that often means "on", "to", or "onto" depending on the context. In this sentence, it indicates the direction of a movement or transfer into an account.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the German possessive pronoun for "your" in the formal form. It’s capitalized here because it’s being used to formally address someone in writing.</div><div><strong>Girokonto</strong> This is a German noun that means "checking account", referring to a bank account used for daily transactions.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German conjunction for "or". It is used to offer a choice between two options.</div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> As before, this is the German possessive pronoun "your" in the formal sense, repeated to address ownership of the second option.</div><div><strong>Sparkonto</strong> This is a German noun meaning "savings account", referring to a bank account intended for saving money over a long term.</div><div>This German sentence could be part of a dialogue in a bank or financial setting where the speaker is asking whether a transaction should be made to the listener’s checking account or savings account, using the formal "you" to show respect.</div>','<h2>Sicher. Möchten Sie normales oder Premium-Benzin?</h2><div><strong>Sicher.</strong> This is the German word for "sure" or "certainly". It’s an affirmative response often used to confirm something or to indicate agreement.</div><div><strong>Möchten</strong> This is the conjugated form of the verb "möchten", which is the subjunctive II of the verb "mögen". It means "would like" in English and indicates a polite desire or preference in this context.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for addressing someone in a formal manner or when talking to strangers. It can refer to both singular and plural.</div><div><strong>normales</strong> This is the German adjective for "regular" or "normal". Here, it describes the type of gasoline being offered and agrees in case, number, and gender with the noun it describes.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German word for "or", used as a conjunction to offer a choice between two options.</div><div><strong>Premium-Benzin</strong> This term is a compound noun. "Premium" is an adjective denoting high quality, and "Benzin" means "gasoline" or "petrol" in English. Together, "Premium-Benzin" refers to high-quality or higher-octane gasoline.</div>','<h2>Werde ich mein Gehalt wöchentlich oder monatlich bekommen?</h2><div><strong>Werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense of the verb "werden", which means "to become" or "will" when forming the future tense. In this question, it signifies that the action (receiving the salary) will occur in the future.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relation to the subject, "ich".</div><div><strong>Gehalt</strong> This noun means "salary" or "wages" in English. It’s the object of the sentence, reflecting what the speaker will receive.</div><div><strong>wöchentlich</strong> This is an adverb meaning "weekly" in English. It describes the frequency at which the speaker is inquiring about receiving their salary.</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "or" in English. It is used here to present an alternative option.</div><div><strong>monatlich</strong> This is an adverb meaning "monthly" in English. Like "wöchentlich", it describes another possibility for the frequency of salary payment.</div><div><strong>bekommen?</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "bekommen", which means "to receive" or "to get" in English. In the context of this question, it’s the action that the subject wants to know about, concerning when it will happen.</div>','<h2>Sehr gut. Möchten Sie einen Kaffee? Oder einen Tee?</h2><div><strong>Sehr gut</strong> This is a German phrase meaning "very good". It can be used to express satisfaction or to affirm that something is well or acceptable.</div><div><strong>Möchten</strong> This is the subjunctive II form (Konjunktiv II) of the German modal verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to want". In this context, it can be translated as "would like to" when making a polite request or offer.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used to politely address someone in a formal setting, similar to the use of "vous" in French.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular form of the indefinite article in German, which means "a" or "an" in English. It precedes a masculine noun in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Kaffee?</strong> This is the German word for "coffee". It is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case because it is the object of the verb "möchten".</div><div><strong>Oder</strong> This is the German word for "or". It is a conjunction used to offer alternatives or choices between two options.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> Again, this is the accusative masculine singular form of the indefinite article, preceding the masculine noun that is the second option offered.</div><div><strong>Tee?</strong> This is the German word for "tea". Like "Kaffee", it is a masculine noun and in this context is in the accusative case as it is the object of the verb "möchten".</div>','<h2>Möchten Sie lieber einen Fensterplatz oder einen Gangplatz?</h2><div><strong>Möchten</strong> This is the polite or formal form of the German modal verb "mögen" in the conditional tense. It expresses a polite request or desire, similar to "would like" in English.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. In this context, it’s used to formally address one or more people.</div><div><strong>lieber</strong> This word means "rather" or "preferably" in English. It’s used here to offer a choice, asking the preference of the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular form of the indefinite article "ein", which means "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun it modifies, here indicating the choice of one of two types of seats.</div><div><strong>Fensterplatz</strong> This is a compound noun in German meaning "window seat". It is composed of the words "Fenster" meaning "window" and "Platz" meaning "place" or "seat".</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the German word for "or", a conjunction used to offer a choice between two alternatives.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> Again, this is the accusative masculine singular form of the indefinite article "ein", preceding the choice of the second type of seat.</div><div><strong>Gangplatz</strong> Like "Fensterplatz", this is a compound noun in German, meaning "aisle seat". It is composed of the words "Gang" meaning "aisle" or "corridor" and "Platz" meaning "place" or "seat".</div><div><strong>?</strong> This is the punctuation mark indicating that the sentence is a question, inviting the addressed person to make a choice between the two options provided.</div>','<h2>Ich würde gern einkaufen gehen oder einen Film schauen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the auxiliary verb "werden" in German. It is used here to express a wish or polite desire, similar to "would like to" in English.</div><div><strong>gern</strong> This is an adverb meaning "gladly" or "willingly" in German. It modifies the verb, indicating a preference or a desire to do something.</div><div><strong>einkaufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to shop" or "to buy" in German.</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is another infinitive form of a verb, "to go" in German. When combined with "einkaufen" it means "to go shopping".</div><div><strong>oder</strong> This is the coordinating conjunction "or" in German. It is used here to connect two options.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular article "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the masculine noun "Film".</div><div><strong>Film</strong> This is a masculine noun in German, meaning "movie" or "film" in English.</div><div><strong>schauen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to watch" or "to look at" in German. Combined with "einen Film", it means "to watch a movie".</div>','<h2>Ich mag alles, aber am meisten Rock und Jazz.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to enjoy". It expresses a preference or fondness for something.</div><div><strong>alles</strong> This means "everything" or "all" in German. It is the direct object in this sentence and denotes a wide, unspecified range of things.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "but" in English. It is used here to introduce a contrast or exception to the previous statement.</div><div><strong>am meisten</strong> This phrase translates to "most of all" or "especially". It is used to indicate a preference hierarchy where the following items are liked more than the rest.</div><div><strong>Rock</strong> This is the German word for the music genre "rock". It is a noun and part of the list of music genres stated as preferred.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is the German word for "and". It is a conjunction used to connect the two preferred music genres in the list.</div><div><strong>Jazz</strong> This is the German word for the music genre "jazz". It is a noun and the second item in the list of preferred music genres.</div>','<h2>Ich liebe mein Auto, aber deins ist schöner.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>liebe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "lieben", which means "to love". It expresses affection or a strong liking for someone or something.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It denotes ownership or association with the subject "Ich".</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neutral noun in German that means "car". It’s the object of the speaker’s affection in this sentence.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a contrast or an exception.</div><div><strong>deins</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "yours" in English. It denotes ownership or association with the person addressed. It’s a contraction of "dein" (yours) and "es" (it, neutral gender) in the context of referring to the car, which is a neutral noun.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "deins" with the adjective "schöner".</div><div><strong>schöner</strong> This is the comparative form of the adjective "schön", which means "beautiful" or "nice". Here, it compares two things, suggesting that the car belonging to the person addressed is more beautiful or nicer than the speaker’s car.</div>','<h2>Regen macht mir nichts aus, aber ich hasse Stürme.</h2><div><strong>Regen</strong> This is the German noun for "rain". It is the subject of the first clause of the sentence.</div><div><strong>macht</strong> This is a form of the German verb "machen", which means "to make" or "to do". Here, it is conjugated in the third-person singular present tense, and it’s used with "mir nichts aus" to convey the expression "doesn’t bother me".</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the dative pronoun "me" in English, indicating the indirect object of the verb "macht" — who is not bothered by the rain.</div><div><strong>nichts</strong> It translates to "nothing" in English, and when combined with "aus" as "nichts aus" it forms the phrase used to express "does not matter" or "is not a problem".</div><div><strong>aus</strong> In this context, "aus" is part of the expression "nichts ausmachen", which means "to not mind" or "to not be bothered by".</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "but" in English. It introduces a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the second clause of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hasse</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "hassen", which means "to hate".</div><div><strong>Stürme</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Sturm", meaning "storms". It is the direct object of the second clause, indicating what the subject hates.</div>','<h2>Aber es ist noch ein Monat bis zu den Ferien.</h2><div><strong>Aber</strong> This is the German word for "but". It is used to introduce a contrast or exception to what has been previously stated.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This corresponds to the English pronoun "it", and is the third-person singular neutral pronoun in German. It’s the grammatical subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state or existence of something.</div><div><strong>noch</strong> This word translates to "still" or "yet" in English. It indicates that a certain period of time continues up to the present or a specified point.</div><div><strong>ein Monat</strong> This phrase translates to "one month" in English. "Ein" is an indefinite article meaning "one", and "Monat" is a masculine noun meaning "month".</div><div><strong>bis zu</strong> This phrase means "until" in English. It is a preposition used to indicate the point in time up to which an event is expected to happen.</div><div><strong>den Ferien</strong> This is the dative plural form of "die Ferien", which translates to "the holidays" or "the vacation" in English. In German, "die Ferien" usually refers to school holidays or a period of time during which someone is not working.</div>','<h2>Ja, aber es ist kein Balkon, es ist eine Terrasse.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It’s an affirmative response to a statement or question.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It serves as a conjunction used to introduce a statement or idea that contrasts with or opposes what has just been mentioned.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and refers to an inanimate object or concept.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the existence or state of being of the subject.</div><div><strong>kein</strong> This word is a negation that combines "kein" (no, not any) with the indefinite article (equivalent to "a" or "an" in English). It negates the existence or presence of the noun that follows it.</div><div><strong>Balkon</strong> This is the German noun for "balcony". It signifies a platform projecting from the wall of a building, typically with a railing or balustrade, accessible via a door or window.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This pronoun is repeated here as the subject for the following clause.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> The verb "sein" appears again to describe the state of being for the subject of the following clause.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the feminine, singular, indefinite article in German, equivalent to the English "a" or "an". It precedes feminine nouns in the singular.</div><div><strong>Terrasse</strong> This is the German noun for "terrace". It refers to an outdoor space, often used like a patio, that can be on ground level or part of a building.</div>','<h2>Ihr mögt mir wohl nicht glauben, aber es ist richtig.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for the second-person plural, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person informally. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mögt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the modal verb "mögen", which can mean "to like" or to "may" in English when expressing possibility. In this context, it conveys the idea "you might" or "you may".</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the German first-person singular dative pronoun, equivalent to "me" in English, used here as an indirect object showing who might not be believed.</div><div><strong>wohl</strong> This word can have various shades of meaning and is often used for emphasis or as a modal particle. In this context, it suggests probable assumption and can be translated as "probably" or "presumably".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German negation word, equivalent to "not" in English. It negates the verb "mögt glauben", indicating disbelief.</div><div><strong>glauben</strong> This is the German verb meaning "to believe".</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "but". It is used to introduce a contrast or an exception to what has been previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the German neutral pronoun for the third-person singular, equivalent to "it" in English. It is the subject of the second part of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicate.</div><div><strong>richtig</strong> This is an adjective meaning "right", "correct", or "proper" in English. It serves as the complement of the verb "ist", completing the meaning of the statement.</div>','<h2>Beide Autos sind schön, aber ich will dieses.</h2><div><strong>Beide</strong> This is the German word for "both". It denotes that the speaker is referring to two things, in this case, cars, which are considered jointly.</div><div><strong>Autos</strong> This is the plural form of "Auto", which means "car" in German. It indicates that the speaker is talking about more than one car.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject with the adjective that describes it.</div><div><strong>schön</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "beautiful" or "nice". It is used here to describe the cars.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a contrast or an exception.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s used as the subject of the second clause.</div><div><strong>will</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want". It expresses the speaker’s desire or intention.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is the neuter form of the demonstrative pronoun "dieser", which means "this" in English. It specifies which car the speaker wants, choosing one of the two mentioned cars.</div>','<h2>Ich mag keine Filme, aber jener da gefällt mir.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to enjoy" in English.</div><div><strong>keine</strong> This is the negative article for plural nouns in accusative case, equivalent to "no" in English, indicating a dislike or absence of something.</div><div><strong>Filme</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Film", which means "movie" or "film" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to contrast two clauses.</div><div><strong>jener</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the nominative masculine singular form, equivalent to "that one" in English, referring to a specific object or person that is away from the speaker.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This word translates to "there" in English, and in this context, it points to a specific movie that is being referred to.</div><div><strong>gefällt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gefallen", which means "to please" or "to be pleasing to" in English. In German, when you like something, you would say it pleases you, hence why "gefallen" is used.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in the dative case, equivalent to "me" in English. It’s the indirect object of the sentence, indicating who is pleased by the movie referred to.</div>','<h2>Sein Kajak ist sehr alt, aber das ist ihm egal.</h2><div><strong>Sein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the third-person singular masculine form, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates ownership or relation to the subject (his kayak).</div><div><strong>Kajak</strong> This is a noun in German, identical to "kayak" in English. It is the object of the sentence, the item being described.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being of the subject (the kayak).</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows (old).</div><div><strong>alt</strong> This is an adjective meaning "old" in English. It describes the condition of the kayak.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect contrasting clauses.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a neutral demonstrative pronoun or article meaning "that" in English. In this sentence, it refers back to the fact of the kayak being very old.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is again the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", meaning "to be". It’s used here with "egal" to express a feeling of indifference.</div><div><strong>ihm</strong> This is a dative pronoun in the third-person singular, equivalent to "to him" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the sentence – to whom the state of the kayak being old is irrelevant.</div><div><strong>egal</strong> This word means "doesn’t matter" or "is indifferent" in English. It’s an adjective used to describe something of no importance or concern to someone.</div>','<h2>Unser Land ist groß, aber ihres ist sehr groß.</h2><div><strong>Unser</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the nominative case for neuter or masculine or plural in German, meaning "our". It indicates possession, referring to "our country" in this sentence.</div><div><strong>Land</strong> This is a neuter noun in German that means "country" or "land". It is the subject of the first clause in the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It’s used here to link the subject "Land" to its adjective "groß".</div><div><strong>groß</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "big" or "large". It is the predicate of the first clause describing "Land".</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a conjunction in German meaning "but". It is used to introduce a contrast or exception to the statement made in the first clause.</div><div><strong>ihres</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the nominative case, for feminine or plural in German, referring to "their country" in this context. It’s in the third-person feminine singular form because "Land" is a neuter noun, and this matches the gender and number.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> Just as the first "ist", this is also the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein". Here it is used in the second clause to link the subject implied by "ihres" to the predicate "sehr groß".</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb in German that means "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>groß</strong> Like the first occurrence, this adjective means "big" or "large", but it is amplified by "sehr" to imply a larger size than in the first clause.</div>','<h2>Ich mag Rock "n" Roll, aber ich mag Jazz auch.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like". It indicates that the speaker has a preference or fondness for something.</div><div><strong>Rock "n" Roll</strong> This is a borrowed phrase from English, used in German as well. It refers to the genre of music that originated in the United States in the early to mid-1950s.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This word translates to "but" in English. It’s a conjunction used to express a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>ich mag</strong> This repetition of "ich mag" reinforces the subject’s likes, introducing a second preference.</div><div><strong>Jazz</strong> Similar to "Rock "n" Roll", this is a noun referring to another genre of music, known for its use of improvisation and rhythmic complexity, originally developed in the African-American communities in the United States</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too" in English. It adds the information that the speaker likes something in addition to what has already been mentioned.</div>','<h2>Ich würde gerne schlafen aber mein Mann schnarcht.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden", which means "to become" or as an auxiliary verb forms the future tense. Here, it’s used to express the conditional mood, equivalent to "would" in English.</div><div><strong>gerne</strong> This word translates to "gladly" or "willingly" in English. It indicates a preference or desire in this context, equivalent to "like to" when used with a verb.</div><div><strong>schlafen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to sleep" in English. When used with "würde" and "gerne", it expresses a wish or condition - "would like to sleep".</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a conjunction in German which means "but" in English. It is used to introduce a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is the first-person singular possessive pronoun in the masculine nominative case in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates ownership or relation to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Mann</strong> This is a German noun meaning "man" or "husband" in English. Here, it refers to the speaker’s husband.</div><div><strong>schnarcht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "schnarchen", which means "to snore" in English. It indicates that the action of snoring is currently taking place.</div>','<h2>Okay. Das ist ein bisschen früh, aber das ist mir recht.</h2><div><strong>Okay</strong> This is a German interjection commonly used in English as well. It signifies acceptance or agreement.</div><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the neuter definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It also serves as a demonstrative pronoun here, meaning "that".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be".</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the indefinite article "a" or "an" in English, used here for the masculine or neuter noun that follows.</div><div><strong>bisschen</strong> This word means "a little" or "a bit" in English. It modifies the adjective that follows to indicate a small amount or degree.</div><div><strong>früh</strong> This is an adjective that translates to "early" in English. It describes timing that is sooner than expected or preferred.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This conjunction means "but" in English. It introduces a statement that contrasts with what has been said before.</div><div><strong>das</strong> Used again, this pronoun refers back to the earlier idea of being early.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> As before, this is the third-person singular present tense form of "sein", meaning "to be".</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular dative pronoun in German, equivalent to "to me" in English.</div><div><strong>recht</strong> This adjective means "right", "just", or "fine" in English. In this context, it means the speaker is okay with or agrees with the situation. The phrase "ist mir recht" translates to English as "is fine with me" or "is okay by me".</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);